{"parse":{"title":"Suasoria","pageid":37321055,"revid":720124034,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><div class=\"thumb tright\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:222px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Statue_of_Roman_poet_Ovid_in_Constanta,_cropped.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/e/e7/Statue_of_Roman_poet_Ovid_in_Constanta%2C_cropped.jpg/220px-Statue_of_Roman_poet_Ovid_in_Constanta%2C_cropped.jpg\" width=\"220\" height=\"470\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/e/e7/Statue_of_Roman_poet_Ovid_in_Constanta%2C_cropped.jpg/330px-Statue_of_Roman_poet_Ovid_in_Constanta%2C_cropped.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/e/e7/Statue_of_Roman_poet_Ovid_in_Constanta%2C_cropped.jpg/440px-Statue_of_Roman_poet_Ovid_in_Constanta%2C_cropped.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"1404\" data-file-height=\"2999\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Statue_of_Roman_poet_Ovid_in_Constanta,_cropped.jpg\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div>The Latin poet <a href=\"/wiki/Ovid\" title=\"Ovid\">Ovid</a> enjoyed his suasoria.</div></div></div>\n<p><b>Suasoria</b> is an exercise in <a href=\"/wiki/Rhetoric\" title=\"Rhetoric\">rhetoric</a>; a form of <a href=\"/wiki/Declamation\" title=\"Declamation\">declamation</a> in which the student makes a speech which is the <a href=\"/wiki/Soliloquy\" title=\"Soliloquy\">soliloquy</a> of an <a href=\"/wiki/Historical_figure\" title=\"Historical figure\">historical figure</a> debating how to proceed at a critical junction in their life.<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Origin\">Origin</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Suasoria&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: Origin\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>The exercise was used in <a href=\"/wiki/Ancient_Rome\" title=\"Ancient Rome\">ancient Rome</a>, where it was, with the <i><a href=\"/wiki/Controversia\" title=\"Controversia\">controversia</a></i>, the final stage of a course in rhetoric at an <a href=\"/wiki/Academy\" title=\"Academy\">academy</a>.  One famous instance was recalled by <a href=\"/wiki/Juvenal\" title=\"Juvenal\">Juvenal</a> in the first of his <i><a href=\"/wiki/Satires_(Juvenal)\" title=\"Satires (Juvenal)\">Satires</a></i>:<sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<table class=\"cquote pullquote\" role=\"presentation\" style=\"margin:auto; border-collapse: collapse; border: none; background-color: transparent; width: auto;\">\n<tbody><tr>\n<td style=\"width: 20px; vertical-align: top; border: none; color: #B2B7F2; font-size: 40px; font-family: &#39;Times New Roman&#39;, Times, serif; font-weight: bold; line-height: .6em; text-align: left; padding: 10px 10px;\">\u201c\n</td>\n<td style=\"vertical-align: top; border: none; padding: 4px 10px;\">\n<p><i>Et nos ergo manum ferul\u00e6 subduximus: et nos<br /></i>\n<i>Consilium dedimus Syll\u00e6 privatus ut altum<br /></i>\n<i>Dormiret.  Stulta est clementia cum tot ubique<br /></i>\n<i>Vatibus occurras peritur\u00e6 parcere chart\u00e6.<br /><br /></i>\nI too have felt the master's cane upon my hand.  I too<br />\nhave given Sulla advice to retire into a deep<br />\nsleep.  No point in sparing paper which is doomed to<br />\ndestruction as you meet all those 'bards' everywhere.\n</p>\n</td>\n<td style=\"width: 20px; vertical-align: bottom; border: none; color: #B2B7F2; font-size: 40px; font-family: &#39;Times New Roman&#39;, Times, serif; font-weight: bold; line-height: .6em; text-align: right; padding: 10px 10px;\">\u201d\n</td></tr>\n\n</tbody></table>\n<p>Here Juvenal recalls his speech advising the dictator <a href=\"/wiki/Sulla\" title=\"Sulla\">Sulla</a> to retire.  Another Roman poet who recalled enjoying his suasoria was <a href=\"/wiki/Ovid\" title=\"Ovid\">Ovid</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Suasoria&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite id=\"CITEREFBloomer2010\" class=\"citation\">Bloomer, W. Martin (2010), \"Roman Declamation: The Elder Seneca and Quintilian\", <i>A Companion to Roman Rhetoric</i>, John Wiley &amp; Sons, pp.&#160;301\u2013302, <a href=\"/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number\" title=\"International Standard Book Number\">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href=\"/wiki/Special:BookSources/9781444334159\" title=\"Special:BookSources/9781444334159\">9781444334159</a></cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=A+Companion+to+Roman+Rhetoric&amp;rft.atitle=Roman+Declamation%3A+The+Elder+Seneca+and+Quintilian&amp;rft.pages=301-302&amp;rft.date=2010&amp;rft.isbn=9781444334159&amp;rft.aulast=Bloomer&amp;rft.aufirst=W.+Martin&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ASuasoria\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-2\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite id=\"CITEREFSusanna_Morton_Braund1997\" class=\"citation\">Susanna Morton Braund (1997), \"Declamation and contestation in satire\", <i>Roman Eloquence: Rhetoric in Society and Literature</i>, Routledge, p.&#160;147, <a href=\"/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number\" title=\"International Standard Book Number\">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href=\"/wiki/Special:BookSources/9780415125444\" title=\"Special:BookSources/9780415125444\">9780415125444</a></cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=bookitem&amp;rft.atitle=Declamation+and+contestation+in+satire&amp;rft.btitle=Roman+Eloquence%3A+Rhetoric+in+Society+and+Literature&amp;rft.pages=147&amp;rft.pub=Routledge&amp;rft.date=1997&amp;rft.isbn=9780415125444&amp;rft.au=Susanna+Morton+Braund&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ASuasoria\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-3\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation\">\"Education (Roman)\", <i><a href=\"/wiki/Encyclopaedia_of_Religion_and_Ethics\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Encyclopaedia of Religion and Ethics\">Encyclopaedia of Religion and Ethics</a></i>, <b>9</b>, <a href=\"/wiki/Charles_Scribner%27s_Sons\" title=\"Charles Scribner&#39;s Sons\">Charles Scribner's Sons</a>, 1912, p.&#160;212</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=bookitem&amp;rft.atitle=Education+%28Roman%29&amp;rft.btitle=Encyclopaedia+of+Religion+and+Ethics&amp;rft.pages=212&amp;rft.pub=Charles+Scribner%27s+Sons&amp;rft.date=1912&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ASuasoria\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n</ol></div></div>\n<table class=\"metadata plainlinks stub\" role=\"presentation\" style=\"background:transparent\"><tbody><tr><td><a href=\"/wiki/File:Nuvola_apps_bookcase.svg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"Stub icon\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a5/Nuvola_apps_bookcase.svg/30px-Nuvola_a